<HL>
   International -- Washington Insight:
   U.S. Analysts Say Soviet Democratic Shift
   Is Genuine but See Problems for Moscow
   ----
   By Walter S. Mossberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- U.S. intelligence analysts say the Soviet
Union's move toward democracy is probably irreversible, and
they believe the nation will become a multiparty democracy in
the 1990s.
   This assessment, according to senior administration
officials familiar with the intelligence analyses, is
tempered with warnings that the road to Soviet democracy will
be rocky. The analysts say that the Soviet economy is headed
for more chaos and fragmentation, that several of the 15
Soviet republics will be leaving the union and that the
Kremlin will face a new wave of ethnic violence and strikes
as national groups and independent trade unions gain power.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Still, says a senior administration official, explaining
the intelligence community's view: "There's a real decent
chance that democratic trends will continue and be
consolidated. It's better than 50-50." The official says the
Soviet Union's current experiment with democracy at every
level of government "goes much deeper" than the attempts at a
liberal system during the feeble pre-Bolshevik Kerensky
government in 1917. And, the official adds, "It will be
harder to resist."
   This generally positive assessment reinforces President
Bush's and Secretary of State James Baker's personal
admiration for Mikhail Gorbachev, who unleashed the
democratization process and hopes to be its beneficiary, and
it may be one reason Mr. Bush is standing so firmly by Mr.
Gorbachev.
   Even if a hard-line dictator were to oust the current
regime, the intelligence community doesn't believe he could
block the march of democracy for more than a few years. "At
this point, they can't totally arrest it," the senior
official says.
   But in this analysis, the good news about democracy is
balanced by bad news for Soviet leaders on just about every
other front. U.S. analysts say that as power flows from the
Kremlin to Soviet republics and local governments, violence
will grow. "Newly enfranchised ethnic majorities will be
settling scores with local minorities," the official says.
   On top of these troubles, U.S. analysts take a dim view of
Soviet economic prospects. Exports of oil and weapons are
expected to keep falling, further squeezing the supply of
hard currency needed to finance imports of food and consumer
goods. The country's external debt and trade deficit are
expected to mount ominously.
   The intelligence agencies don't offer any precise
predictions on the political outcome of all this. Mr.
Gorbachev is expected to hang on to political control for the
foreseeable future, but the central government and party he
heads are expected to lose power. In any case, the analysts
say, he's unlikely to be in power for the decade or more that
will be required to carry out even those reforms that have
already been started.
   The intelligence agencies now take a generally more
positive view of maverick Russian Republic chief Boris
Yeltsin, who caused a stir Thursday by publicly resigning
from the Soviet Communist Party. Mr. Yeltsin used to be
written off as a lightweight demagogue. But, said the
official who discussed the agencies' analysis: "We overuse
the word `demagogue.' Yeltsin is a complex figure. He's the
most obvious national figure" among the reformers.
   The intelligence community concedes that some of Mr.
Yeltsin's behavior has been bizarre and self-destructive,
probably indicating a mild emotional or psychological
problem. But he is viewed as a first-rate political
strategist, someone who is more intelligent than he seems and
is worthy of U.S. respect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900716-0098
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900716-0098.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Greenspan Statement Intended to Damp
   Expectations of New Moves to Cut Rates
   ----
   By Alan Murray and Tom Herman
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   By describing Friday's credit-easing move as a technical
matter, Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan has
signaled that further moves to cut interest rates shouldn't
be expected soon.
   The Fed took action that resulted in a modest cut in the
so-called federal funds rate, which is the rate banks charge
on loans to each other. That move, which caused the rate to
drop to just over 8% from its previous level of 8 1/4%, could
cause other short-term interest rates to fall as well.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Fed's rate-cutting move came after a week of seemingly
contradictory pronouncements by the Fed chairman.
   In a private meeting with senators last week, Mr.
Greenspan argued that because the civilian jobless rate had
fallen to 5.2%, the Fed had little room to stimulate the
economy without sparking inflation.
   Then, in congressional testimony on Thursday, Mr.
Greenspan made the unusual announcement that the Fed might
ease modestly, not to help a sluggish economy but rather to
"offset" any effect of the credit crunch on bank-loan rates.
   The message behind those confusing statements: The Fed's
easing move should be viewed as a one-time correction and not
as the first of a series of easing moves.
   The Fed's action comes after weeks of intensifying
pressure from the Bush administration to cut rates. Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady had even taken the unusual step of
complaining publicly about interest rates in a series of
recent interviews.
   Administration officials were pleased with the Fed's
action Friday. But they also understood that the Fed chairman
was doing so grudgingly. "There is a consistent pattern of
lagging" at the Fed, one official said. "This is better than
nothing, but it's late and insufficient."
   In any event, the Fed's move should ease the pressure Mr.
Greenspan will feel Wednesday, when he is scheduled to give
Congress his mid-year review of monetary policy.
   On Wall Street, the Fed's action was seen partly in a
political context. The move "certainly doesn't hurt
politically," said Donald J. Fine, chief market analyst at
Chase Manhattan Bank. "It takes some of the pressure off the
Fed and alleviates some of the criticism . . . regarding Fed
restrictiveness."
   Despite Mr. Greenspan's elaborate qualifications, Mr. Fine
believes the Fed will have to take more rate-cutting action
this year. "I think further ease will come, but not for a
while, not until they see definitive evidence of a
sustainable moderation in inflation," he said.
   The credit-easing move had a calming effect on long-term
interest rates, which fell slightly after the Fed's action.
Nevertheless, some investment managers fear the Fed may be
easing too soon. "I think the Fed is a little premature" in
easing credit now, said Wayne F. Wong, managing director at
Marinvest Inc., a money-management firm based in New York.
"The faster you ease, the sooner inflation will come back."
   In explaining his plans to ease credit, Mr. Greenspan
cited bank data showing that rates banks charge on loans have
risen slightly relative to the federal funds rate. He also
noted that growth in the nation's money supply has been
sluggish recently. According to Fed sources, Mr. Greenspan's
conclusions were drawn partly from banking data that weren't
readily available to the public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
