<HL>
   Prudential-Bache Plans
   New Marketing Strategy
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- In the battle to pull in new mutual-fund
customers, Prudential-Bache Securities is planning a new
strategy: Let 'em in free.
   Prudential-Bache, which runs the country's 13th largest
fund group with $17 billion in assets, has asked the
Securities and Exchange Commission for permission to sell its
mutual funds to customers of other broker-sold mutual funds
-- without charging a sales commission.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Prudential-Bache spokesman declined to comment on the
filing, noting that the SEC still hasn't declared it
effective. But others note that, while Prudential-Bache, a
unit of Prudential Insurance Co. of America, may be the
largest fund group ever to make such an offer, its offer
isn't unique.
   "We've done it for three years, and we're not the first,"
said Edward Mahoney, president of AMEV Advisers Inc., which
allows owners of other broker-sold funds to buy AMEV funds,
provided they show proof that they sold the other fund within
the previous 60 days.
   The idea is to allow a broker to switch a customer between
funds without the client's being charged two sets of
commissions.
   What has Prudential-Bache got to attract other fund
customers? Kanon Bloch Carre &amp; Co., a Boston mutual-fund
research firm, gives high marks to Prudential-Bache's utility
fund, its intermediate-term government-bond fund and its
convertible-bond fund. But overall, Kanon Bloch ranks
Prudential's fund family as 40th out of 94.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900716-0082
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900716-0082.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Tapie Expected to Disclose
   Financing for Adidas Deal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARIS -- Bernard Tapie and his lead banker are promising
today to confound the skeptics who said he would have trouble
completing his takeover of West German sporting goods giant
Adidas AG.
   After a week's negotiations, his lead banker said it has
arranged the financing package that Mr. Tapie had said he
would disclose today. Credit Lyonnais's Societe de Banque
Occidentale unit announced Friday that it has more offers of
funds than Mr. Tapie needs. (One of Mr. Tapie's other main
banks, Credit Agricole, said Friday that it didn't have
enough information to make a decision.)
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Although Mr. Tapie has refused so far to disclose the
price of the Adidas purchase, it seems likely to be well
above the 889 million French franc ($160.5 million) market
valuation of Bernard Tapie Finance S.A., his main holding
company. So far, the flamboyant French financier hasn't
explained how he will fund the takeover or how it will affect
his other companies.
   Because of that, French securities regulators last week
ordered trading suspended in Bernard Tapie Finance and its
two listed subsidiaries, industrial scale-makers Terraillon
S.A. and Testut S.A. It was after the suspension that Mr.
Tapie promised to disclose financial details today.
</TEXT>
