<HL>
   Business Brief -- Bundaberg Sugar Co.:
   Company's Operating Profit
   Rose 24% for Fiscal 1990
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A
</SO>
<CO>
   A.BBS
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Bundaberg Sugar Co. of Australia reported that after-tax
operating profit for the year ended April 30 rose 24% to 28.2
million Australian dollars (US$22.5 million) from A$22.8
million a year earlier.
   An estimated 10.7% increase in the price of sugar to A$361
a metric ton-equal to about 2,204.62 pounds -- boosted
profit, the company said, and all major sectors of the
company performed strongly. Bundaberg forecast in February
that its profit would rise at least 15%, largely because of
higher sugar prices.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Pretax operating profit rose 25% to A$46.8 million from
A$37.5 million. The company had extraordinary profit of
A$32.7 million from selling its interest in a coal joint
venture; the year-earlier period didn't have any special
item. Proceeds were used partly to eliminate long-term debt
and purchase assets to strengthen core businesses, Bundaberg
said.
   Revenue increased 6.8% to A$299.9 million from A$280.8
million.
   The dividend was raised 33% to 20 cents a share from 15
cents.
</TEXT>
