</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900716-0055.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   MEI Forgoes LecTec Takeover in Favor
   Of Salon and Employee Leasing Ventures
   ----
   By Richard Gibson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MEI LECT
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MINNEAPOLIS -- MEI Diversified Inc., which is redefining
its name, is seeking to enter the employee leasing and beauty
salon businesses but is backing away from a medical products
acquisition, its president said.
   "We're a company in transition," Donald E. Benson said,
disclosing that MEI no longer is committed to acquiring
LecTec Corp., which makes medical tape, sensors and other
devices. "We've come to the conclusion that in relation to
other transactions pending that we should not give up those
three million shares" LecTec would cost. Still, he said MEI
may take a minority position in LecTec.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   MEI hopes to close by mid-August on the acquisition of a
chain of department-store beauty salons, which would
represent about $400 million in annual revenue. It is looking
also into the employee leasing business, by which MEI would
buy employees from small companies and then lease them back.
Mr. Benson indicated that MEI is pursuing an unidentified
entity that would become the nucleus of that business.
   He said such rebuilding efforts are likely to result in a
slightly larger loss for the year than in 1989, when MEI lost
$5.5 million, or 29 cents a share, on sales of $205.4
million. While he wouldn't quantify the anticipated loss --
it depends partly on a pending audit following the recent
sale of its snack and candy businesses -- Mr. Benson said he
expects the second half to be flat to slightly profitable.
   MEI reported a first-quarter loss of $4.5 million, or 24
cents a share, on sales of $44.7 million. In the second
quarter MEI sold its candy and snack units to Ezaki Glico Co.
of Osaka, Japan, for $58 million. Mr. Benson said those units
were becoming slim-margin commodity businesses.
   It is understood that MEI has hired Salomon Brothers to
seek buyers for its nut business, which represented about
one-third of first-quarter revenue.
   MEI expects to retain a healthy balance sheet, with
perhaps $75 million in cash and equivalents after the pending
salon acquisition, Mr. Benson said.
   He said that while the acquisition will cost $50 million,
about $25 million in Essanelle Salon Co. debt would be
immediately refinanced, reducing MEI's cash outflow to $25
million. The acquisition also includes Glemby Co. and Maxims.
Terms call for Regis Corp., which owns Essanelle and Maxims,
to retain a 20% interest.
   Because nearly 2,000 beauty salons, in such department
store chains as Sears, Bloomingdales, May Co. and Saks Fifth
Avenue, would be acquired, MEI is seeking approval for the
acquisition under the Hart-Scott-Rodino antitrust law. Still,
the acquisition represents only about 4% of the total salon
market, Mr. Benson said.
   MEI would become essentially a holding company should the
pending transactions occur, Mr. Benson said. He added that
MEI has no plans to retire debt or redeem its shares in the
foreseeable future.
   The LecTec situation has changed because MEI believes it
could achieve better leverage elsewhere, Mr. Benson said.
Still, MEI could end up with a position in the
medical-products field, because it lent LecTec $45 million to
acquire New Dimensions in Medicine, a unit of Baxter
Healthcare Corp. That loan was secured with New Dimensions
stock.
   Mr. Benson said LecTec is expecting an investment banker
to advise its management soon on its various options. Should
MEI take a position in LecTec, Mr. Benson said it probably
would be in the range of 700,000 to one million of LecTec's
3.2 million shares outstanding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900716-0054
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900716-0054.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   World Bank Recommends Boosting Aid
   To Nations Trying to Reduce Poverty
   ----
   By Peter Truell
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST MDEST AFRIC EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- At least a quarter of the world's population
-- or more than one billion people -- now live on less than
$370 a year, the World Bank says. The international agency
adds that the number of poor people could be cut as much as
40% by the end of the century if poor countries provide
income-earning opportunities and basic social services.
   In the meantime, developed countries should maintain or
increase their levels of aid, the World Bank says in its
annual development report. But the aid should be tightly
linked to a country's efforts to reduce poverty, the report
advises.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   More than half of the poorest peoples live in South Asia,
in countries such as India and Bangladesh, with most of the
remainder living in East Asia and sub-Saharan Africa.
   The report, which is being released today, focuses on
poverty. It sets out a dual strategy for improving the lot of
the world's poor-people who survive on about a dollar a day
or less.
   But for poverty to be reduced appreciably, many developing
countries will have to alter their current policies, the bank
says. It is scathing about some strategies: "Many past
policies meant to benefit the rural poor have failed; land
reform barely helped the poor, except after wars or
revolutions; subsidized credit programs not only benefited
the rich much more than the poor but ran into serious
debt-repayment problems; and excessive taxation of
agriculture contributed to poor results."
   Too often, the report says, formal social security plans
and health policies have failed to benefit the poorest
people. It says that targeted food subsidies often work
better than general food subsidies, and also recommends
public-employment programs.
   Through such policies, some countries have had remarkable
success in shrinking poverty. For example, Indonesia reduced
the share of its population living in poverty to less than
20% from 60% in less than a generation, according to Lyn
Squire, who led the team that authored the report.
   Controlling population growth is another challenge facing
the poorest countries. The World Bank estimates that another
850 million people will be born in the remainder of the
decade. In sub-Saharan Africa in particular, fast population
growth threatens to worsen poverty.
   Donor countries too, will have to make sure they provide
enough aid to countries making serious efforts to reduce
poverty, the report says. On current projections, aid is
expected to increase 2% a year, according to the Paris-based
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development. That
implies aid will total $64 billion in the year 2000, up 25%
from $51 billion in 1988.
   World Bank President Barber Conable told reporters
recently that as "the Cold War wanes, developed countries can
afford more aid." He added that if developed countries cut
their military spending by 10% they could double their aid."
   If donor countries were more generous and pegged their aid
at the "widely accepted" level of 0.7% of gross national
product, aid could increase to as much as $144 billion by the
end of the century, the World Bank says. Among rich nations,
Saudi Arabia, the Scandinavian countries and Holland are the
most generous when aid is measured as a percentage of GNP.
Saudi Arabia's aid in 1988 totaled 2.7% of national output,
the World Bank says. Ireland and the U.S. are the least
generous, with aid totaling about 0.2% of GNP, the
international agency says, quoting OECD figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
