<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE FED EASED interest rates modestly, but signaled that
further reductions shouldn't be expected soon. The central
bank pushed down the federal funds rate, which banks charge
each other for loans. That could cause other short-term
interest rates to decline as well.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices surged, with the Dow Industrials closing at a
record 2980.20, up 10.40 points, after trading above the 3000
level briefly. The dollar rose, but analysts said the credit
easing could hurt the weak U.S. currency.
   ---
   RJR Nabisco said it is beginning a $6.9 billion
refinancing to retire many of its junk bonds by open-market
purchases and an exchange offer.
   ---
   Eastern Airlines' lawyers are expected to confer with
federal officials today on how the carrier will respond to
criminal charges that it falsified maintenance and safety
records.
   ---
   Cummins Engine agreed to sell a 27% stake to Ford Motor,
Tenneco and Kubota Ltd. for $250 million. The complex deal
could mean hundreds of millions of dollars in added revenue
for the diesel-engine maker.
   ---
   The SEC charged an "unknown" group of investors with
insider trading in Contel securities in connection with the
company's $6.2 billion plan to merge with GTE Corp.
   ---
   Producer prices rose 0.2% in June and retail sales
increased 0.5%, suggesting that inflation is somewhat under
control and that consumer spending may be in a modest upturn.
   ---
   U.S. auto makers plan to boost third-quarter domestic
output 11.6%, despite recent cutbacks by Ford and weak sales.
However, sales of U.S.-built cars rose a surprisingly strong
2.5% in the first 10 days of July.
   ---
   Persian Gulf oil exporters will hold down current
production in return for larger shares of OPEC output later.
   ---
   Federal regulators asked a court to block R.R. Donnelley's
planned $487.5 million purchase of a printing venture owned
by Meredith Corp. and members of a West German family.
   ---
   A New York state panel recommended that Nynex's New York
Telephone unit cut current rates by $81 million, and rejected
the firm's proposed $919.7 million increase.
   ---
   Thornburgh said he won't appoint an independent counsel to
investigate Neil Bush, the president's son, in the $1 billion
failure of a Denver thrift unless he is accused of a crime.
   ---
   General Development said a judge rejected the company's
plea-bargain agreement with the government involving an
alleged conspiracy to defraud thousands of home buyers.
   ---
   The Commodity Exchange's new president will be David
Halperin, executive vice president of the New York Mercantile
Exchange, according to a person close to the exchanges.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 215,600,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2980.20, up 10.40; transportation 1187.59, up 22.63;
utilities 206.17, off 0.32.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3447.56, up
14.76.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.22, up 0.22; spot
index 133.28, up 0.90.
   Dollar: 148.15 yen, up 0.85; 1.6510 marks, up 0.0170.
