<HL>
   Business Brief -- Micron Products Inc.:
   Creditors Force Numedco
   Into Bankruptcy Proceedings
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PMR
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   Micron Products Inc., New York, said unsecured creditors
of its troubled Numedco Inc. subsidiary have moved to force
Numedco into bankruptcy-law proceedings.
   Micron said the creditors filed a complaint in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in Philadelphia. Rather than undergo
involuntary proceedings, Numedco will ask for protection
under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code, Micron said.
Under Chapter 11, a company continues to operate, with
protection from creditor lawsuits, while working out a plan
to settle debts.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Kuno Laren, chairman of Micron, said Numedco, which has
been unprofitable for seven quarters, has been attempting to
sell assets to satisfy secured debt. Mr. Laren estimated that
the unsecured creditors, unpaid since June 6, are owed $3
million.
   Micron is a maker of medical products; Numedco, which is
curtailing operations, has been a distributor of medical and
surgical supplies. According to Mr. Laren, the parent company
hasn't guaranteed any of Numedco's unsecured debts.
   Micron said its manufacturing business remains profitable
"and will continue."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900716-0021
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900716-0021.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Cambrex Corp.:
   Venture Seeks Part of Line
   Of American Cyanamid Co.
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CBAM ACY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Cambrex Corp., a specialty chemical maker based in East
Rutherford, N.J., said it intends to become the majority
partner in a joint venture that would acquire part of the
textile-chemical business of American Cyanamid Co., a Wayne,
N.J., maker of chemicals and pharmaceuticals.
   The parties declined to disclose terms of the proposed
transaction. But Cambrex said the operations to be acquired
include Cyanamid's textile-chemical plant in Charlotte, N.C.,
and have annual sales exceeding $20 million. The deal is
subject to a definitive pact, board approvals and other
conditions. Cyanamid confirmed that the transaction outlined
by Cambrex is under negotiation, but it declined to say why
it would sell the textile-chemical operations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cambrex's minority partner in the venture would be an
investor group led by L. David Moore, an executive most
recently with Interchem Inc., then an Atlanta unit of RTZ
Corp., London. Reached in Atlanta, Mr. Moore said he left
Interchem as president last October, shortly after it was
acquired by Rhone-Poulenc S.A. of France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900716-0020
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900716-0020.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Southeast Banking Corp.:
   Net Loss of $20.7 Million
   Is Posted for 2nd Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
07/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   STB
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Southeast Banking Corp., Miami, reported a second-quarter
net loss of $20.7 million, or 66 cents a share, reflecting a
previously announced surge in nonperforming assets.
   Southeast had net income of $32.3 million, or $1 a share,
a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In mid-June, Southeast said it expected to report a
second-quarter loss because of the worsening condition of the
Florida real-estate market. In line with that expectation,
the banking company said nonperforming assets rose to $619
million as of June 30, from $474 million at March 31. The
reserve for loan losses was boosted to $279 million, or 2.73%
of loans, from $258 million at the end of March.
   Nonperforming assets are loans that have been foreclosed
or are more than 90 days past due. Loan-loss reserves are a
fund that banks set aside to offset expected losses from bad
loans.
   For the first half, Southeast reported a loss of $77.5
million, or $2.41 a share, compared with earnings of $65.4
million, or $2.04 a share, a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
